# Chapter 10 — Measurement, Superposition, and the Qubit

An afternoon on Helgoland, June 1925. Werner Heisenberg has fled to the treeless North Sea island to escape a punishing bout of hay fever, and he has brought a problem with him: how to build a theory of atomic transitions that traffics only in quantities you can actually observe — never the electron orbits no one has ever glimpsed. On that island he works out the skeleton of matrix mechanics. But the deeper question lurking beneath his arithmetic is one that every physicist after him would be forced to face: when you measure something quantum, what happens?

Not in the abstract. Not philosophically. Concretely: you run an experiment, you get a result — what were the rules?

---

## The Measurement Postulate

Let $\hat{A}$ be a Hermitian observable with discrete eigenvalues $\{a_n\}$ and orthonormal eigenstates $\{|a_n\rangle\}$. When you measure $\hat{A}$ on a system in state $|\psi\rangle$, three things happen:

**1.** The only possible outcomes are the eigenvalues $a_n$. Nothing between them. Not a superposition of them. Exactly one.

**2.** The probability of getting $a_n$ is

$$\boxed{P(a_n) = |\langle a_n|\psi\rangle|^2.}$$

This is the Born rule. The inner product $\langle a_n|\psi\rangle$ is a complex amplitude; its modulus squared is the probability. Geometrically, $P(a_n)$ is the squared projection of $|\psi\rangle$ onto $|a_n\rangle$.

**3.** Immediately after the measurement returns $a_n$, the state is $|a_n\rangle$.

This is collapse. Not a metaphor — the state-update rule.

The probabilities sum to 1 by the completeness of the eigenstates:

$$\sum_n P(a_n) = \sum_n |\langle a_n|\psi\rangle|^2 = \langle\psi|\!\left(\sum_n |a_n\rangle\langle a_n|\right)\!|\psi\rangle = \langle\psi|\hat{I}|\psi\rangle = 1.$$

Nothing leaks. The interpretation of collapse is contested — "Still Puzzling" at the end of the chapter lays out the current state of that debate. The practical content is not in dispute: after getting outcome $a_n$, you predict subsequent measurements using $|a_n\rangle$.

---

## The Two-State System

The simplest arena where all of this is computable by hand is the qubit: a two-dimensional complex Hilbert space $\mathbb{C}^2$. Pick a basis $\{|0\rangle, |1\rangle\}$. The most general normalized state is

$$|\psi\rangle = \alpha|0\rangle + \beta|1\rangle, \qquad \alpha, \beta \in \mathbb{C}, \qquad |\alpha|^2 + |\beta|^2 = 1.$$

Two real parameters fix the state up to a global phase. An electron's spin, a photon's polarization, the two lowest energy levels of a superconducting circuit — all are physical qubits, and the mathematics is one and the same for every one of them.

The standard observables on a qubit are the Pauli operators:

$$\sigma_x = \begin{pmatrix}0 & 1\\1 & 0\end{pmatrix}, \qquad \sigma_y = \begin{pmatrix}0 & -i\\i & 0\end{pmatrix}, \qquad \sigma_z = \begin{pmatrix}1 & 0\\0 & -1\end{pmatrix}.$$

Each is Hermitian, each squares to the identity, each has eigenvalues $\pm 1$. Their commutators read $[\sigma_i, \sigma_j] = 2i\epsilon_{ijk}\sigma_k$, so for instance $[\sigma_x, \sigma_z] = -2i\sigma_y \neq 0$. They do not commute — which means measuring one after another in different orders gives different results.

One warning about $\sigma_y$: the upper-right entry is $-i$, not $+i$. This is the single most common sign slip in qubit calculations. The matrix is Hermitian despite looking antisymmetric as a real matrix, because Hermitian means equal to the *conjugate* transpose — the transpose of $\sigma_y$ is $-\sigma_y$, but the conjugate transpose is $+\sigma_y$. The $i$ does the work. Any code touching qubit calculations should verify $\sigma_y^\dagger = \sigma_y$ at startup.

---

## The Stern-Gerlach Experiment

In 1922 Otto Stern and Walther Gerlach sent a beam of silver atoms through an inhomogeneous magnetic field. Classical physics predicted a smear — a continuous spread of deflections matching the continuous range of magnetic-moment orientations. What appeared on the plate was two discrete spots. Quantization, written in silver, three years before anyone had a theory to explain it.

The field gradient pushes with a force proportional to $\mu_z$, the component of the magnetic moment along the field axis. Were angular momentum classical, $\mu_z$ would be continuous and the deposit would be a streak. Instead: two spots, at $\mu_z = \pm\mu_B$. The Born rule is not abstract here. It is etched into the silver.

The observable is $\hat{S}_z = (\hbar/2)\sigma_z$, with eigenvalues $\pm\hbar/2$. An atom in state $|\psi\rangle = \alpha|\!\uparrow\rangle + \beta|\!\downarrow\rangle$ lands on the upper spot with probability $|\alpha|^2$ and on the lower with $|\beta|^2$. Let only the upper beam through and the atoms that survive are in state $|\!\uparrow\rangle$ — collapsed, certain, ready to be used again.

The interesting physics lives in sequence. Three arrangements:

**Z then Z.** Select the $|\!\uparrow\rangle$ beam from a first Z apparatus and feed it into a second. Every atom hits the upper spot. Probability 1. If you know the outcome of an $\hat{S}_z$ measurement, measuring $\hat{S}_z$ again returns the same result — collapse is stable.

**Z then X.** The $\hat{S}_x$ eigenstates are $|\pm x\rangle = (|\!\uparrow\rangle \pm |\!\downarrow\rangle)/\sqrt{2}$. An atom in $|\!\uparrow\rangle$ is an equal superposition of both $\hat{S}_x$ eigenstates, so a subsequent X measurement comes out 50/50. The atom that was certainly spin-up in Z is wholly uncertain in X.

**Z then X then Z.** After the X measurement, the state collapses to $|+x\rangle$ or $|-x\rangle$. Either way, that state is a 50/50 superposition in Z: $|+x\rangle = (|\!\uparrow\rangle + |\!\downarrow\rangle)/\sqrt{2}$. The subsequent Z measurement is again random. The intermediate X measurement erased the Z information. Measure Z, then X, then Z: the Z certainty is gone.

This is not instrumental clumsiness. It is $[\sigma_x, \sigma_z] \neq 0$ made physically tangible. You cannot simultaneously hold definite values for both.

